### Smart Pointers in Rust

Smart pointers are data structures that act like pointers but also have additional metadata and capabilities. They implement the `Deref` and `Drop` traits.

---

### Common Smart Pointers

| Type | Ownership | Use Case |
|------|-----------|----------|
| `Box<T>` | Single owner | Heap allocation, trait objects |
| `Rc<T>` | Shared (reference counted) | Multiple read-only owners |
| `Arc<T>` | Atomic shared | Thread-safe shared ownership |
| `RefCell<T>` | Single owner | Interior mutability |
| `Mutex<T>` | Thread-safe | Mutual exclusion |
| `Cell<T>` | Single owner | Copy types interior mutability |

---

### Key Traits

```rust
// Deref - allows smart pointers to be used like references
use std::ops::Deref;

struct MyBox<T>(T);

impl<T> Deref for MyBox<T> {
    type Target = T;
    fn deref(&self) -> &T {
        &self.0
    }
}

// Drop - custom cleanup when value goes out of scope
impl<T> Drop for MyBox<T> {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        println!("Dropping MyBox");
    }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Smart pointers implement `Deref` for auto-dereferencing and `Drop` for automatic cleanup. Choose the right smart pointer based on ownership and concurrency needs: `Box` for single ownership, `Rc` for shared ownership in single-threaded, `Arc` for multi-threaded.

codeExample:
use std::ops::Deref;

struct CustomBox<T>(T);

impl<T> CustomBox<T> {
    fn new(x: T) -> CustomBox<T> {
        CustomBox(x)
    }
}

impl<T> Deref for CustomBox<T> {
    type Target = T;
    fn deref(&self) -> &T {
        &self.0
    }
}

impl<T> Drop for CustomBox<T> {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        println!("CustomBox dropped");
    }
}

fn main() {
    let x = 5;
    let y = CustomBox::new(x);

    assert_eq!(5, *y);  // dereference works
    println!("Value: {}", *y);
}
